            <p>We’ve been thinking carefully about having a reasonable pricing practice, with the intention of making image licensing accessible to a wider public. Having a Single User license help us to maintain lower prices. Let us know your thoughts about it.</p>

            <h2>I think that 40% of license fee for authors is not fair. Why don’t you raise it?</h2>
            <p>Well, we’ve been working hard to build a trustworthy image bank, and that includes thinking about what would be a fair profit distribution and royalty rate practice, considering that the donation is an essential part of our model.</p>
            <p>One of our biggest challenges is to make the photo licensing process more simple and accessible, and it includes a simple and reasonable pricing.</p>
            <p>Think of it, everyone has at least one great photo archived somewhere in a hard drive; there are billions of great iPhone shots that are just kept in monthly backups, and they would probably never be turned into money at all, neither in delight for photo lovers eyes!</p>
            <p>So, what about turning “nothing" into a 20-dollar photo that will earn you 40% of the fee for each license sold and, still more, generating a compulsory contribution of 20% directly to a humanitarian cause! Doesn’t it sound great enough?</p>
            <p>Initially, licensing your photos at Klloom will earn you 40% royalties out of the gross profit on every Standard License sold. We assure you this rate won’t be reduced, and we do consider raising that in the future. But, before that, we need to look at the big picture. It’s not only about earning some money, it’s about striving to prove that it is possible to have an economic model where monetization and social altruism can walk together.</p>

            <h2>Why am I asked to enter a PayPal email?</h2>
